## Cloud SQL setup (one-time)

```bash
# Create instance
gcloud sql instances create {{PROJECT_NAME}}-pg \
  --region europe-west1 \
  --database-version POSTGRES_16 \
  --tier db-f1-micro \
  --enable-private-ip \
  --network <your-vpc>

# Enable connection pooling (REQUIRED before --max-instances > 1)
gcloud sql instances patch {{PROJECT_NAME}}-pg \
  --enable-pooling

# Create database + user
gcloud sql databases create {{PROJECT_NAME}} --instance {{PROJECT_NAME}}-pg
gcloud sql users create {{PROJECT_NAME}} --instance {{PROJECT_NAME}}-pg --password <strong-password>
```

Stash the password in Secret Manager as `DATABASE_PASSWORD`. Cloud Run reads via the Secret Manager mount.

## Cloud Tasks queue (drop this section if your project doesn't use Cloud Tasks)

```bash
gcloud tasks queues create {{PROJECT_NAME}}-jobs \
  --location europe-west1 \
  --max-attempts 5 \
  --max-backoff 600s \
  --max-doublings 4
```

## Cost expectations (Phase 2 baseline)

Roughly ~$10/month fixed before customer #1 — see the cost summary in your Tech Stack design doc. Most of this is the Cloud SQL micro instance.

## Deploy via GitHub Actions

### Prerequisites (one-time)

- Create GCS bucket `{{PROJECT_NAME}}-prod-eu` (europe-west1)
- Create Cloud SQL Postgres instance `{{PROJECT_NAME}}-pg` in europe-west1
- Create Cloud Tasks queue `{{PROJECT_NAME}}-jobs` in europe-west1 (if applicable)
- Create the Secret Manager secrets your `cloud_run.yaml` references
- Create service accounts: `{{PROJECT_NAME}}-app@`, `{{PROJECT_NAME}}-deploy@`, `{{PROJECT_NAME}}-scheduler@`
- Set up Workload Identity Federation for GitHub Actions
- GitHub repo secrets: `GCP_PROJECT`, `GCP_WORKLOAD_IDENTITY_PROVIDER`, `GCP_DEPLOY_SERVICE_ACCOUNT`

### Deploy

Trigger the `Deploy to Cloud Run` workflow from the GitHub Actions UI. It builds the image, pushes to Artifact Registry, replaces the Cloud Run service, and smoke-tests `/healthz`.

For the full step-by-step (with verifications and recovery steps for every failure mode), see `DEPLOY.md`. Read `ACCOUNTS.md` first to register the external services you'll need.
